Ms Phelps had been out shopping with her mother last Friday lunchtime when she got the call from next-door neighbour Belinda Standbridge, 45, urging her to get home.

Miss Standbridge - whose house was also badly damaged - had been in bed asleep for 20 minutes when the fire began, but she said her smoke alarms did not go off because they were faulty.

However Merlin Housing said the alarms in her home are mains wired, battery backed-up units that were installed in 2010 and found to be working perfectly when inspected this June.

